		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I&#8217;m a little disappointed in this recipe.  I just made them for Christmas Eve dessert, thought they&#8217;d be a nice touch since there isn&#8217;t any snow here right now.  The cookie crumbled apart.  After cooked it just would not stay together and I ended up throwing the last bit of the dough out.  I was not happy with the taste.  I was expecting them to be excellent, and they were subpar&#8230; I felt like I missed an ingredient, and continuously checked, but didn&#8217;t miss a thing.  They were an okay cookie, I&#8217;m not sure I would do them again.  I must say though, adding the nut definitely made it better&#8230; pecans!  Thanks for the recipe anyway.  Do you possibly know what happened to my cookies?  Maybe I prepared them incorrectly?</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/12/snowball-cookies/?replytocom=215140#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-215140", "215140", "respond", "13767")'>Reply</a>		</div>

		<ul class='children'>

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-blueviolet bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-215143">

		
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.anutinanutshell.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Blueviolet</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://www.anutinanutshell.com/2011/12/snowball-cookies/comment-page-11/#comment-215143">December 24, 2011 at 6:39 pm</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I&#8217;m so sorry that they didn&#8217;t come out right for you. I&#8217;ve actually never had them crumble like that before, and I&#8217;m just not sure what might have caused that to happen. I usually take them out of the oven, when I see they have a slight golden color and are set. I do need to handle them gently, and I put them on the cooling rack for about 5-10 minutes before I roll them for the first time. Most people do like them with the nuts, as it adds quite a bit of flavor, but I wanted to make sure that people knew they could be made with or without.</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/12/snowball-cookies/?replytocom=215143#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-215143", "215143", "respond", "13767")'>Reply</a>		</div>

		</li>

	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-216126">

		
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn">Leslie</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://www.anutinanutshell.com/2011/12/snowball-cookies/comment-page-11/#comment-216126">December 30, 2011 at 9:49 pm</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I think the secret is letting them set for a few minutes after baking and handling them gently, like Blueviolet said. The first time I made these cookies, I immediately put them in the sugar, and a bunch of them crumbled on me, but the second time I tried Blueviolet&#8217;s idea, and it worked really well. I hope you get the same result, if you decide to try again. <img src='http://www.anutinanutshell.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_surprised.gif' alt=':o' class='wp-smiley' /> )</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/12/snowball-cookies/?replytocom=216126#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-216126", "216126", "respond", "13767")'>Reply</a>		</div>

		</li>
</ul>
</li>

	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-215578">

		
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn">Nadia</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://www.anutinanutshell.com/2011/12/snowball-cookies/comment-page-11/#comment-215578">December 28, 2011 at 10:06 pm</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I make a variation of these (no powdered sugar in the mix) that I know as Mexian Wedding Cookies.  As I&#8217;m making them in a warmer climate, I chill the dough a bit before rolling and because I do use pecans, I really knead the dough so the flour and butter are distributed. Also, don&#8217;t be tempted to overbake them. I take them out when they are slightly golden but bake them at 350 for 15 minutes. They are delicious.</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/12/snowball-cookies/?replytocom=215578#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-215578", "215578", "respond", "13767")'>Reply</a>		</div>

